{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_id_s8_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"76aeca",
"children":[
"The Pneumonia Severity Index (PSI) and Infectious Disease Society of America/American Thoracic Society (IDSA/ATS) scoring systems help predict site of care."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_id_s8_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"32380f",
"children":[
"Empiric therapy for MRSA should be considered in patients with one of these risk factors:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"987772",
"children":[
"previous treatment for MRSA infection (strongest risk factor)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"cb0037",
"children":[
"hospitalization or parenteral antibiotic administration in the preceding 90 days"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"42732e",
"children":[
"preceding influenza-like illness"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"199e69",
"children":[
"a suspicious Gram stain (gram-positive cocci in clusters)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"aa4c70",
"children":[
"conventional therapy failure"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"f1d37b",
"children":[
"injection drug use or pleural-based lung nodules (suggesting septic pulmonary emboli)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"1f98c5",
"children":[
"cavitary lung lesions"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"c2a85a",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Pseudomonas"
]
},
" should be considered in:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"2a08d4",
"children":[
"infection with this bacterium in the preceding year (strongest risk factor)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"d12b2b",
"children":[
"immunocompromised patients"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"5835cb",
"children":[
"patients with underlying structural lung disease (bronchiectasis or cystic fibrosis)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"db3e4e",
"children":[
"medical conditions requiring repeated courses of antibiotics"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"cb0037",
"children":[
"hospitalization or parenteral antibiotic administration in the preceding 90 days"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"bdcb54",
"children":[
"Anaerobic infections are uncommon causes of CAP. For patients in whom a concern exists for aspiration who can be treated in the ambulatory setting, amoxicillin or amoxicillin-clavulanate is recommended. In hospitalized patients with CAP, the addition of anaerobic coverage is recommended only if lung abscess or empyema is present."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"56e98c",
"children":[
"Patients with CAP who test positive for influenza should also be treated with an antiviral agent regardless of duration of illness before diagnosis."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a4b5bb",
"children":[
"For patients with uncomplicated CAP who demonstrate rapid defervescence and clinical improvement over the first 3 days, a 5-day course of therapy is adequate for cure."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"525fe9",
"children":[
"Exceptions to short antibiotic course (3-5 days) include:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"48aafd",
"children":[
"patients with cavitary disease or lung abscess, empyema"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"93f625",
"children":[
"concomitant bacteremia"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"83fe81",
"children":[
"extrapulmonary infection"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"ed6487",
"children":[
"ongoing instability (persistent fever, abnormal vital signs, or hypoxia)"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"2",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_id_s8_inline_t2"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"01ee28",
"children":[
"Glucocorticoids are not routinely recommended in CAP and should be reserved for patients with documented adrenal insufficiency or refractory septic shock."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"92137d",
"children":[
"Macrolides (azithromycin and clarithromycin) are recommended as monotherapy only for pneumonia in nonhospitalized patients if the regional prevalence of pneumococcal resistance to this class is known to be less than 25%."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"9f7ea2",
"children":[
"Macrolides and quinolones may prolong the QT interval, and alternative agents should be considered in patients at risk for torsades de pointes, including those with a history of a long QT interval, those taking other medications that can prolong the QT interval, and those with electrolyte abnormalities."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"5fe966",
"children":[
"Follow-up chest x-ray is not routine; consider in adults aged >50 years with risk factors for lung cancer."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
}
]
},
